const SP1 = "Mr Halloran kept his shop exactly as his father had left it: the same brass scales, the same jars of boiled sweets gone cloudy with age, the same hand-lettered sign forbidding credit. Customers were fewer each year, and he knew it, but when the supermarket opened on the corner he only polished his counter a little harder and arrived a little earlier, as though punctuality alone might hold back the tide. He never once spoke of closing. To say the word aloud would have been to admit that the shop, and perhaps he himself, belonged to a world that no longer had any use for them.";
const SP2 = "The letter had sat on the hall table for three days before Eleanor opened it. She told herself she was simply busy, that the garden needed tending and the accounts were behind; but each time she passed the small white envelope she walked a little faster, as one hurries past a window one does not wish to look through. When at last she broke the seal, the words inside were briefer and kinder than she had feared, and she sat for a long while holding them, surprised to find that dread, once met, weighs so much less than dread imagined.";
const SP3 = "Tomas had been warned that the city would change him, and he had laughed at the warning, certain that a person carried his home inside him like a coin sewn into a coat. For the first year he wrote letters describing the strangeness of everything. By the third year the letters had stopped, not because he had forgotten his village but because he no longer found it strange that he had two lives, and could no longer say with confidence which of them was the disguise.";

const PO1 = "The orchard that we planted young\nnow leans its weight against the wall;\nwe meant to pick the fruit ourselves\nbut left it, season after season, to fall.\n\nStill every spring it tries again,\nas if forgetting were a kind of grace,\nand offers to the empty lane\nthe blossom no one comes to face.";
const PO2 = "They built the lighthouse for the ships,\nbut the ships have found another way;\nthe keeper climbs the stair each night\nand lights a lamp for empty bay.\n\nCall it duty, call it pride,\nor the simple need to keep a vow:\nhe turns the great lens to the dark\nand asks of no one why, or how.";
const PO3 = "I thought the river argued with the stone,\nall summer long, in one unbroken word;\nbut autumn showed me, when the banks were bare,\nit was the stone that shaped what I had heard.\nThe water only borrowed, for a while,\nthe stubborn sentence it appeared to say,\nand carried, when I was not listening,\nthe quiet of the stone it wore away.";

const SB1 = "Supporters of the new screen-time limits point to the steep rise in reported anxiety among teenagers over the past decade, a rise that closely tracks the spread of smartphones. Critics, however, note that the same period saw rising academic pressure, falling household incomes in many regions, and a growing willingness to report mental-health concerns that once went unspoken. To read the correlation as proof that screens cause anxiety is to mistake a crowded room for an empty one: the variable we have named may simply be the one we happened to be looking for.";
const SB2 = "It is often claimed that a society can be judged by how it treats its prisoners. The principle is appealing, but it conceals a difficulty. Treatment that one era calls humane, a later era may call cruel, and a third may call indulgent; the standard moves with the values of the judge. Perhaps the more revealing measure is not the comfort a society offers those it has condemned, but the care it takes before condemning them at all.";
const SB3 = "When a policy succeeds, its supporters credit its design; when it fails, they blame its execution. The arrangement is convenient, because it makes the policy itself unfalsifiable: no outcome can ever count against it. A genuine test would require its advocates to state, in advance, what result would persuade them they were wrong. Until they do, what is offered as evidence of success is better understood as an article of faith.";

